name: palm date production, conditioned and dried | palm date, conditioned and dried | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/15363/documentation

This dataset represents 1 kg of palm date fruit conditioned and dried in Tunisia. All the exchanges are calculated per kg of palm date and are based on field data from the main industrial palm date exporter in Tunisia. The inventory includes the following activities: sorting, washing, fumigating, cooling, heating, drying and glucosing. The packaging has not been taking into account.Regarding waste management, palm date kernel are recovered as animal feed. The annual productivity of the plant is 13000 tons of palm dates Deglet Noor (97% of the plam dates are conventionals). The cultivar of the dates studies is Deglet Noor. Tunisia is the world's largest exporter of Deglet Noor. 

The activity starts when palm date fruit arrives to the plant in order to be conditioned. 

The activity ends when the fruit has undergone all processing steps. The palm date is then ready to  be packed and send to the importing country. The facility, the infrastructures and the machineries has not been taking into account.
category: C:Manufacturing/10:Manufacture of food products/103:Processing and preserving of fruit and vegetables/1030:Processing and preserving of fruit and vegetables

processDocumentation.geographyDescription: The inventory is an extrapolation  modeled for Tunisia and is based on field data from one of the main exporter of the Country. Tunisia is the world's largest exporter of Deglet Noor. The conditioning takes place in a plant located in Beni Khalled (in northern tunisia).
processDocumentation.samplingDescription: The main palm date conditioning is located in the north of Tunisia. The value were collected from one of the main exporter of Deglet Noor in Tunisia (13'000 tons each year). It has been validated and complemented by literature data. The values are not average data from many exporter.

exchanges.description: Methyle bromide is now used to sanitize the fruit, during the process of fumigation. This pesticide is now forbidden by the Montreal Protocole on Ozone depleting substances. The entreprise is planneing to used phostoxin starting 2015.  The worst case scenario is modelized, where all the bromomethane is released to the athmosphere. This product is only used for the conventional palm dates, as a subsitute to the freezing process.
